Hi! ... we're back!

* So why?

Back in 2008 Brian Aker had been wondering for a long time about all of the
changes post MySQL 4.1, and a group of us agreed with him.
We believed there is a large market of users who never wanted them, and never
cared for them. Brian also wanted to question the foundations of what we built.
Do users want wrong data? How often is the query cache really valuable? If
everyone just has a root user with all privs, why carry the baggage of the
ACL code. Etc.

* What is the goal?

A micro-kernel that we then extend to add what we need (all additions come
through interfaces that can be compiled/loaded in as needed).  The target
for the project is web infrastructure backend and cloud components.

* Is this a product of Sun/MySQL?

No! In case you didn't notice, Sun/MySQL were bought by Oracle.

* Wait, Sun funded this at one point in time?

YES! Can you believe it? They bought MySQL, then funded a team of us to
go work on a fork. One wonders how they went from being the dot in .com to
becomming the Oracle Hardware Division. Or, really, no one doens't wonder.

* What company is driving this then?

Amazingly enough, some of us remember a day when people worked on Free Software
because they wanted to. That's what this is.

Drizzle's license is the GPL v2. It's written by those who show up.

* So what are the differences between is and MySQL?

No modes, views, triggers, prepared statements, stored procedures, query
cache, data conversion inserts, ACL. Fewer data types.  Less engines, less
code.  Assume the primary engine is transactional.

* Why now?

Why not now :)

* No really, that was Brian's answer in the original FAQ. Why NOW?

Funny story. Drizzle was right about so many things, but as they say timing
is everything. Drizzle pioneered what became OpenDev's gated development process,
used protobufs for replication, is fully configurable via environment variables
and is super self-contained.

Problem is, gRPC hadn't been released, nor had docker. I don't even think the
cloud native manifesto had been written yet. So people thought a bunch of
this was strange.

Oh, also, Oracle bought Sun, MongoDB was Web Scale, the core team moved to
Rackspace but ended up founding OpenStack and Drizzle, ahead of its time as
it was, went softly into this good night.

I've been meaning to revive it for a while now. But then, I made friends
named Claude and Hermes and the task of forward-porting 15-year old code
no longer seemed insane.

* "This is awesome, but I need you to add back..."

Cool! We're pluggable!

* What platforms?

Linux

(see also, just build the container)

But seriously, I'm not playing games with trying to make it compile on your
Mac Laptop, because there is no reasonable CI story for that. And also, I don't
care if it runs on your Mac Laptop. It's a database. If you want it on a Mac,
or on Windows ... run it in a linux container.

* What is the future?

Whatever our new AI overlords decide.

* Can I get involved?

Most certainly. There is plenty to do. Find me on Matrix. If there are more
than 2 of us, we'll make a channel.

* Should I email the mailing list with patches?

Please god no, we live in the age of the Internet :)

We use OpenDev.

* What is the target?

Deliver a microkernel that we can use to build a database that meets the
needs of a web/cloud infrastructure. To this end we are exploring http
interfaces, sharding enhancements, etc... do not expect an Oracle, MySQL,
Postgres, or DB2.

There is no GA date at the moment.

We are focusing on multi-core architecture. This is not designed to run on a
wrist watch (hint, go use SQLite). We support both 32bit and 64bit but the
class of machine we are targetting is 64bit. We are making design decisions
which assume very large amounts of RAM will be made available to the DB.

* Can I run a website with this?

Sure! I believe in you. You can do anything you want.

* Is Brian still involved

Sadly I haven't talked to Brian in a long time. I'm pretty sure he's moved
on to other things.

* Why drizzle?

Brian is from Seattle. Monty lives there now. Drizzle is our normal form of
"rain" but it is not "rain", it is drizzle. This was a bit of a rainy day project
that finally found a spot in his schedule, and now history has repeated
and it's found its way into mine :)

  -Monty
    still channelling Brian
